# Project Build Workflow

## Ground Rules

- Execute steps sequentially. Never proceed without explicit user confirmation.
- At the end of every session, update `session-state.mdc` before stopping.
- At the start of every session, read `session-state.mdc`, `features.mdc`,
  `architecture.mdc`, and `decisions.mdc` before taking any action.
- Never contradict a locked `.mdc` file without flagging the conflict
  explicitly and getting confirmation to update it.

---

## Step 0 — Clarifying Questions

Ask all ambiguous questions upfront. Cover:

- Who are the users and what's the core user journey?
- Any hard constraints (auth required? multi-tenant? offline support?)
- Preferred languages/frameworks if not specified
- Success criteria — what does "done" look like for v1?

Do not proceed until all questions are answered.

---

## Step 1 — Lock Features (`features.mdc`)

Create `features.mdc` with two sections:

**Core (building now):**

- Exhaustive list of v1 features with acceptance criteria per feature
- Each feature tagged with priority (P0/P1/P2)

**Extensible (future, not building):**

- List of anticipated future features
- Note any architectural decisions that must be made now to support them later

Confirm with user before locking.

---

## Step 1.5 — Lock UI Style (`ui-style.mdc`)

After features are locked, define the visual language before any frontend code is written.
Record decisions in `ui-style.mdc`; reference it throughout Step 5. **Defaults below apply to
every project** unless the user explicitly overrides.

**Lock in `ui-style.mdc`:**

- **Aesthetic** — modern minimal, production-grade startup: clean whitespace, neutral palette,
  one accent, sharp typography, subtle shadows/borders. No gradients or decorative clutter.
  Stack: shadcn/ui pattern (Tailwind + HSL CSS vars in `:root`/`.dark` + CVA). Inter via
  Google Fonts in `index.css`.
- **Branding** — before any UI code, use `GenerateImage` for a concept-driven icon (never a
  plain letter): `frontend/public/logo.png` (≥512×512), `favicon.svg`, `og-image.png`
  (1200×630). Reference logo in nav, login, and `apple-touch-icon`.
- **`index.html`** — full meta/OG/Twitter tags (`title`, `description`, `theme-color`, `og:*`,
  `twitter:*`, favicon links). Never ship Vite defaults.
- **Dark mode** — default light; sun/moon `ThemeToggle` in app header and landing nav; persist
  `<appname>-theme` in localStorage; `darkMode: 'class'`; inline `<script>` in `index.html`
  before React mounts to prevent flash; light tokens in `:root`, dark in `.dark` (not media query).
- **Landing page** — always at `/`, always public (no auto-redirect when signed in). Sections:
  sticky nav · hero · features · how-it-works · CTA · footer. Signed-in users see "Go to
  Dashboard →" in nav and hero instead of "Sign in". App routes under `/dashboard`, etc.;
  post-login redirect to `/dashboard`.
- **Responsive** — container `max-w-7xl … 2xl:max-w-[1440px]`; hamburger nav on mobile
  (`hidden md:flex` desktop links); 44px touch targets; `grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4` stat grids;
  `break-words`/`break-all` on long paths; `3xl: '1920px'` breakpoint.
- **UX patterns** — skeleton loaders (not spinners) shaped to content; `fade-in` on pages/cards;
  entire list cards clickable via `<Link>` with inline context; per-item settings on dedicated
  pages (never inline on list cards); grouped forms use draft + Save/Discard + toasts (sonner),
  no auto-save; semantic badges with `dark:` variants.

Confirm with user before locking. Once locked, flag any deviation and get confirmation.

---

## Step 2 — Lock Architecture (`architecture.mdc` + `decisions.mdc`)

**`architecture.mdc`** must define:

- Backend: Clean Architecture layers
  (Entities → Use Cases → Interface Adapters → Infrastructure)
- Frontend: Feature-based structure
  (pages / components / hooks / store / services per feature)
- Auth strategy
- Error handling pattern and structured logging approach
- Observability plan (what gets logged, how errors surface in free-tier hosting)
- LLM integration layer (model: Gemini 3.5 Flash or newer with equal/more
  free limits; fallback strategy on rate limits)
- Cover **Concurrency & reliability** — document what is actually implemented; note known gaps explicitly

**`decisions.mdc`** must record every non-obvious decision as:

```
Decision: [what]
Context: [why this was needed]
Alternatives considered: [what else was evaluated]
Rejected because: [concrete reason]
```

Confirm with user before locking.

---

## Step 2.5 — Initialize Session State (`session-state.mdc`)

Create `session-state.mdc` with:

```
Last completed step: 2
Current in-progress: —
Decisions made this session: [list]
Open questions / blockers: [list]
Next immediate action: Start Step 3
```

Update this file at the end of every session without being asked.

---

## Step 3 — Lock Data Contracts (`schema.mdc`)

Define and lock:

- DB schema (tables, columns, types, indexes, FK constraints)
  - Include soft delete, created_at/updated_at on all entities
  - Flag fields added only for future extensibility
- DTOs (request/response shapes per endpoint)
- API contract (OpenAPI spec or equivalent)
  - All endpoints, methods, auth requirements, request/response schemas
  - Error response shapes must be consistent across all endpoints

No implementation starts until schema and API contract are locked.
Confirm with user before locking.

---

## Step 4 — Workspace Setup

1. Verify or create skill/reference files needed for accurate implementation
2. Create `reviewer.mdc` with an explicit review checklist (see below)
3. Confirm tooling: linter, formatter, test runner configured

**`reviewer.mdc` checklist (run against every git diff before commit):**

- [ ] No business logic in controllers/route handlers
- [ ] No direct DB calls outside the repository/data layer
- [ ] All endpoints have auth checks where required
- [ ] No secrets or credentials in code
- [ ] DTOs validated at the boundary (not inside use cases)
- [ ] Every new function has at least one unit test
- [ ] Error responses match the locked error shape from schema.mdc
- [ ] No deviation from architecture.mdc layer boundaries
- [ ] No new external dependency added without updating decisions.mdc

Confirm with user before proceeding.

---

## Step 4.5 — Lock Deployment Config

Define before writing any feature code:

- Hosting targets:
  - Frontend → Vercel (free)
  - Backend → Render or Railway free tier (document cold start behavior)
  - DB → Neon Postgres free tier
  - Vector DB (if needed) → Pinecone free tier (2GB, no expiry)
  - LLM → Gemini free tier via AI Studio (1,500 RPD; add retry/backoff
    for 429s; never hardcode API keys client-side)
- Dockerfile or platform config committed to repo
- `.env.example` with all required vars (no values)
- Before pushing, build and test apps

Confirm with user before proceeding.

---

## Step 5 — Incremental Feature Build

For each feature:

1. Write the contract first (function signatures, interfaces) — confirm
2. Write tests against the contract (before implementation)
3. Implement until tests pass
4. Run reviewer.mdc checklist against git diff
5. Confirm with user before marking feature done and moving to next

**Definition of done per feature:**

- Unit tests pass
- Integration test for the happy path passes
- Reviewer checklist passes with no unchecked items
- **`session-state.mdc` updated** (see Feature Completion Gate below)

**Batching rule:** Once 2-3 features are complete and patterns are
stable, related features in the same domain/layer may be batched.
Never batch across architectural boundaries.

---

## Feature Completion Gate (mandatory)

Before marking **any** feature `DONE` in `session-state.mdc` or moving to the next
feature ID, complete **all** of the following:

1. **Acceptance criteria audit** — Open `features.mdc` for that feature ID. Every
   bullet in acceptance criteria must be verified (automated test, SQL/Redis check, or
   documented manual step). Record pass/fail in session-state under the feature row.

2. **No partial features** — DB tables, interfaces, or `# F-XX` comments alone do **not**
   count as done. If only part of a feature is implemented (e.g. tree-sitter without
   pgvector writes), mark it `PARTIAL` or `DEFERRED` in session-state — never `DONE`.

3. **Explicit deferral when skipping order** — The planned build order in session-state
   is the default. Skipping a feature (e.g. building F-04 before F-03) requires an
   explicit `DEFERRED: F-XX — <reason>` line in session-state **before** starting the
   substitute feature. P0 does not automatically override P1 without recording why.

4. **Integration proof for data features** — Features that persist or queue data must
   have an observable artifact before `DONE`:
   - Embeddings → `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM code_embeddings` > 0 after a test PR
   - Reviews → row in `reviews` + optional GitHub post
   - Queue → message XACK'd; `XPENDING` not growing unbounded
   - "Code exists" or "table migrated" is insufficient.

5. **session-state hygiene** — On every feature boundary update: `Last Completed Step`,
   `Current In-Progress`, and `Next Immediate Action`. Stale "Next action" from earlier
   steps (e.g. Step 4 setup) must be removed or updated — never left contradictory.

6. **Cross-feature comment scan** — Before marking feature N done, grep the diff for
   `# F-<other>` references. Any comment pointing at unfinished work in another feature
   ID is a blocker unless that other feature is marked `PARTIAL` with listed gaps.

---

## Commit Policy

**Never run `git commit` unless the user explicitly asks.**

Finishing a task, passing tests, or updating `session-state.mdc` does **not** authorize a
commit. When work is done but the user has not asked to commit:

1. Summarize what changed
2. Tell the user changes are uncommitted and ready for review
3. Wait for explicit approval

Commit only when the user clearly requests it — e.g. "commit", "commit this", "proceed",
"proceed to next", or "continue" in the Proceed Protocol sense below.

Commit message format: `feat: <feature-id> <short description>` (e.g. `feat: F-05 async worker system`).
Use `chore:` for setup/config steps (e.g. `chore: Step 4.5 deployment config`).
Use `fix:` for bug fixes. One logical change per commit.

---

## Proceed Protocol

When the user says "proceed", "proceed to next", or "continue" **meaning advance to the
next build step**, this means: "I have reviewed and approve the work shown above — commit
it and build the next feature."

1. **Commit the approved work** — stage and commit only the work the user just reviewed.
   Do not start the next feature until the commit succeeds.
2. **Build the next feature** — implement contracts → tests → implementation.
3. **STOP when the feature is complete** — do NOT commit automatically. Instead:
   - Run the reviewer.mdc checklist against `git diff HEAD` (non-staged changes)
   - Present the checklist results and a brief summary to the user
   - Wait for explicit approval before committing

"Proceed" approves the _previous_ feature. The _next_ feature always needs its own
review+approval cycle before it is committed.

If the user says "continue" while reviewing or discussing (not advancing the build),
do **not** commit — ask what they want to do next.

---

## Session Resume Protocol

At the start of any new session, before any action:

1. Read `session-state.mdc`
2. Read `features.mdc`
3. Read `architecture.mdc`
4. Read `decisions.mdc`
5. Summarize current state to user and confirm what to work on next
